<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-235-480  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 235 480.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  March 12 1990 n291 p62(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC proposes telco 'caps.' (Federal Communications Commission)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Casatelli, Christine.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) introduces a pricingpolicy that requires telephone companies to share revenues thatexceed a price ceiling with their customers.andP;  The policy is builton a mechanism that provides higher rates of revenue return tocorrespond with higher return rates on interstate access services.andO;According to FCC Chmn Alfred Sikes, the idea is to provide anincentive for communications service providers to improve theperformance of their networks and increase their productivity.andP;  Atthe same time, he noted, the policy will result in lower chargesfor the ratepayer and provide new opportunities for the telephonecompanies.andP;  MCI Communications Corp, which will pay access chargesto the local telephone companies, dissented, saying that the FCChad not proven that consumers will benefit from these price capregulations.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   MCI Communications Corp. (rules and regulations).andO;Ticker:    MCIC.andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionCommunications Service SuppliersTelephone CompaniesPricing PolicyRevenueProductivity.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>